# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyber-kill-chain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] An **advanced persistent threat** (**APT**) is a stealthy cybersecurity threat, typically manipulated by a state or state-sponsored group, which gains unauthorized access to a computer network and remains undetected for an extended period.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] In recent times, the term may also refer to non-state-sponsored groups conducting large-scale targeted intrusions for specific goals.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Such threat actors' motivations are typically political or economic.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Every major business sector has recorded instances of cyberattacks by advanced actors with specific goals, whether to steal, spy, or disrupt.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] These targeted sectors include government, defense, financial services, legal services, industrial, telecoms, consumer goods and many more.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Some groups utilize traditional espionage vectors, including social engineering, human intelligence and infiltration to gain access to a physical location to enable network attacks.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] The purpose of these attacks is to install custom malware.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] APT attacks on mobile devices have also become a legitimate concern, since attackers are able to penetrate into cloud and mobile infrastructure to eavesdrop, steal, and tamper with data.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] The median "dwell-time", the time an APT attack goes undetected, differs widely between regions.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] FireEye reported the mean dwell-time for 2018 in the Americas as 71 days, EMEA as 177 days, and APAC as 204 days.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Such a long dwell-time allows attackers a significant amount of time to go through the attack cycle, propagate, and achieve their objectives.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Warnings against targeted, socially-engineered emails dropping trojans to exfiltrate sensitive information were published by UK and US CERT organisations in 2005.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] This method was used throughout the early 1990s and does not in itself constitute an APT.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] The term "advanced persistent threat" has been cited as originating from the United States Air Force in 2006 with Colonel Greg Rattray cited as the individual who coined the term.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] The Stuxnet computer worm, which targeted the computer hardware of Iran's nuclear program, is one example of an APT attack.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] In this case, the Iranian government might consider the Stuxnet creators to be an advanced persistent threat.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Advanced persistent threat (APT) as a term may be shifting focus to computer-based hacking due to the rising number of occurrences.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] PC World reported an 81 percent increase from 2010 to 2011 of particularly advanced targeted computer attacks.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Actors in many countries have used cyberspace as a means to gather intelligence on individuals and groups of individuals of interest.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] The United States Cyber Command is tasked with coordinating the US military's offensive and defensive cyber operations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Numerous sources have alleged that some APT groups are affiliated with, or are agents of, governments of sovereign states.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] A Bell Canada study provided deep research into the anatomy of APTs and uncovered widespread presence in Canadian government and critical infrastructure.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Attribution was established to Chinese and Russian actors.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] In incidents analysed by Mandiant, the average period over which the attackers controlled the victim's network was one year, with longest – almost five years.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] The infiltrations were allegedly performed by Shanghai-based Unit 61398 of People's Liberation Army.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Chinese officials have denied any involvement in these attacks.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Previous reports from Secdev had previously discovered and implicated Chinese actors.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] There are tens of millions of malware variations, which makes it extremely challenging to protect organizations from APT.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] While APT activities are stealthy and hard to detect, the command and control network traffic associated with APT can be detected at the network layer level with sophisticated methods.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Deep log analyses and log correlation from various sources is of limited usefulness in detecting APT activities.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] It is challenging to separate noises from legitimate traffic.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Traditional security technology and methods have been ineffective in detecting or mitigating APTs.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Active cyber defense has yielded greater efficacy in detecting and prosecuting APTs (find, fix, finish) when applying cyber threat intelligence to hunt and adversary pursuit activities.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Human-Introduced Cyber Vulnerabilities (HICV) are a weak cyber link that are neither well understood nor mitigated, constituting a significant attack vector.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Multiple organizations may assign different names to the same actor.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] As separate researchers could each have their own varying assessments of an APT group, companies such as CrowdStrike, Kaspersky, Mandiant, and Microsoft, among others, have their own internal naming schemes.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Names between different organizations may refer to overlapping but ultimately different groups, based on various data gathered.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] CrowdStrike assigns animals by nation-state or other category, such as "Kitten" for Iran and "Spider" for groups focused on cybercrime.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies have named groups based on this system — Rampant Kitten, for instance, was named by Check Point rather than CrowdStrike.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Dragos bases its names for APT groups on minerals.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Mandiant assigns numbered acronyms in three categories, APT, FIN, and UNC, resulting in APT names like FIN7.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies using a similar system include Proofpoint (TA) and IBM (ITG and Hive).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] Microsoft used to assign names from the periodic table, often stylized in all-caps (e.g.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/advanced-persistent-threat] POTASSIUM); in April 2023, Microsoft changed its naming schema to use weather-based names (e.g.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] The **cyber kill chain** is the process by which perpetrators carry out cyberattacks.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Lockheed Martin adapted the concept of the *kill chain* from a military setting to information security, using it as a method for modeling intrusions on a computer network.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] The cyber kill chain model has seen some adoption in the information security community.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] However, acceptance is not universal, with critics pointing to what they believe are fundamental flaws in the model.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Computer scientists at Lockheed-Martin corporation described a new "intrusion kill chain" framework or model to defend computer networks in 2011.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] They wrote that attacks may occur in phases and can be disrupted through controls established at each phase.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Since then, the "cyber kill chain" has been adopted by data security organizations to define phases of cyberattacks.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] A cyber kill chain reveals the phases of a cyberattack: from early reconnaissance to the goal of data exfiltration.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] The kill chain can also be used as a management tool to help continuously improve network defense.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Weaponization: Intruder creates remote access malware weapon, such as a virus or worm, tailored to one or more vulnerabilities.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Exploitation: Malware weapon's program code triggers, which takes action on target network to exploit vulnerability.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Installation: Malware weapon installs an access point (e.g., "backdoor") usable by the intruder.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Command and Control: Malware enables intruder to have "hands on the keyboard" persistent access to the target network.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Actions on Objective: Intruder takes action to achieve their goals, such as data exfiltration, data destruction, or encryption for ransom.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Deny: Prevent information disclosure and unauthorized access.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Disrupt: Stop or change outbound traffic (to attacker).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Degrade: Counter-attack command and control.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Deceive: Interfere with command and control.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Senate investigation of the 2013 Target Corporation data breach included analysis based on the Lockheed-Martin kill chain framework.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] It identified several stages where controls did not prevent or detect progression of the attack.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Different organizations have constructed their own kill chains to try to model different threats.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] FireEye proposes a linear model similar to Lockheed-Martin's.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] In FireEye's kill chain the persistence of threats is emphasized.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] This model stresses that a threat does not end after one cycle.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Initial Intrusion: Once the attacker has gathered enough information, they attempt to breach the target system or network.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] This could involve exploiting vulnerabilities in software or systems, utilizing social engineering techniques to trick users, or using other methods to gain initial access.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Establish a Backdoor: After gaining initial access, the attacker often creates a backdoor or a persistent entry point into the compromised system.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] This ensures that even if the initial breach is discovered and mitigated, the attacker can still regain access.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Obtain User Credentials: With a foothold in the system, the attacker may attempt to steal user credentials.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] This can involve techniques like keylogging, phishing, or exploiting weak authentication mechanisms.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Install Various Utilities: Attackers may install various tools, utilities, or malware on the compromised system to facilitate further movement, data collection, or control.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] These tools could include remote access Trojans (RATs), keyloggers, and other types of malicious software.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Privilege Escalation / Lateral Movement / Data Exfiltration: Once inside the system, the attacker seeks to elevate their privileges to gain more control over the network.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] They might move laterally within the network, trying to access more valuable systems or sensitive data.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Data exfiltration involves stealing and transmitting valuable information out of the network.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Maintain Persistence: This stage emphasizes the attacker's goal to maintain a long-term presence within the compromised environment.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] They do this by continuously evading detection, updating their tools, and adapting to any security measures put in place.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Among the critiques of Lockheed Martin's cyber kill chain model as threat assessment and prevention tool is that the first phases happen outside the defended network, making it difficult to identify or defend against actions in these phases.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Similarly, this methodology is said to reinforce traditional perimeter-based and malware prevention-based defensive strategies.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] Others have noted that the traditional cyber kill chain isn't suitable to model the insider threat.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] This is particularly troublesome given the likelihood of successful attacks that breach the internal network perimeter, which is why organizations "need to develop a strategy for dealing with attackers inside the firewall.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] They need to think of every attacker as [a] potential insider".
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] The unified version of the kill chain is an ordered arrangement of 18 unique attack phases that may occur in an end-to-end cyberattack, which covers activities that occur outside and within the defended network.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] As such, the unified kill chain improves over the scope limitations of the traditional kill chain and the time-agnostic nature of tactics in MITRE's ATT&CK.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] The unified model can be used to analyze, compare, and defend against end-to-end cyberattacks by advanced persistent threats.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/cyber-kill-chain] A subsequent whitepaper on the unified kill chain was published in 2021.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The **Lockheed Martin Corporation** is an American defense and aerospace manufacturer.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] It is headquartered in North Bethesda, Maryland, United States.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company was formed by the merger of Lockheed Corporation with Martin Marietta on March 15, 1995.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin operates 4 divisions: Lockheed Martin Aeronautics (39% of 2024 revenues); Lockheed Martin Missiles and Fire Control (18% of 2024 revenues); Lockheed Martin Rotary and Mission Systems (24% of 2024 revenues); and Lockheed Martin Space (18% of 2024 revenues).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] As of 2023, it is the top contractor of the United States federal government, and has been since at least 2008.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] As of 2024, 73% of the company's revenue came from the federal government, including 65% from the United States Department of Defense.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2024, 26% of revenue was from sales of the F-35 fighter.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin is also a contractor for the U.S.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Department of Energy and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] It also provides products and services to the Department of Defense and the Department of Energy to the Department of Agriculture and the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] It is involved in surveillance and information processing for the CIA, the FBI, the Internal Revenue Service (IRS), the National Security Agency (NSA), the Pentagon, the Census Bureau, and the Postal Service.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company has received the Collier Trophy six times, including in 2001 for being part of developing the X-35/F-35B LiftFan Propulsion System and in 2018 for the Automatic Ground Collision Avoidance System (Auto-GCAS).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin currently produces the F-35 and leads the international supply chain, leads the team for the development and implementation of technology solutions for the new USAF Space Fence (AFSSS replacement), and is the primary contractor for the development of the Orion command module.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company also invests in healthcare systems, renewable energy systems, intelligent energy distribution, and compact nuclear fusion.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Merger talks between Lockheed Corporation and Martin Marietta began in March 1994, with the companies announcing their $10 billion planned merger on August 30, 1994.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The headquarters for the combined companies would be at Martin Marietta headquarters in North Bethesda, Maryland.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The deal was finalized on March 15, 1995, when the two companies' shareholders approved the merger.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The segments of the two companies not retained by the new company formed the basis for L-3 Communications, a mid-size defense contractor in its own right.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin also later spun off the materials company Martin Marietta Materials.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company's executives received large bonuses directly from the government as a result of the merger.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Augustine, who was at the time CEO of Martin Marietta, received an $8.2 million bonus.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Both companies contributed important products to the new portfolio.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed products included the Trident missile, P-3 Orion maritime patrol aircraft, U-2 and SR-71 Blackbird reconnaissance airplanes, F-117 Nighthawk, F-16 Fighting Falcon, F-22 Raptor, C-130 Hercules, A-4AR Fightinghawk and the DSCS-3 satellite.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Martin Marietta products included Titan rockets, Sandia National Laboratories (management contract acquired in 1993), Space Shuttle External Tank, Viking 1 and Viking 2 landers, the Transfer Orbit Stage (under subcontract to Orbital Sciences Corporation) and various satellite models.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On April 22, 1996, Lockheed Martin completed the acquisition of Loral Corporation's defense electronics and system integration businesses for $9.1 billion, the deal having been announced in January.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The remainder of Loral became Loral Space & Communications.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin abandoned plans for an $8.3 billion merger with Northrop Grumman on July 16, 1998, due to government concerns over the potential strength of the new group; Lockheed/Northrop would have had control of 25% of the Department of Defense's procurement budget.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] For the Mars Climate Orbiter, Lockheed Martin incorrectly provided NASA with software using measurements in US Customary force units when metric units were expected; this resulted in the loss of the Orbiter at a cost of $125 million.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The development of the spacecraft cost $193 million.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In addition to their military products, in the 1990s Lockheed Martin developed the texture mapping chip for the Sega Model 2 arcade system board and the entire graphics system for the Sega Model 3, which were used to power some of the most popular arcade games of the time.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In May 2001, Lockheed Martin sold Lockheed Martin Control Systems to BAE Systems.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On November 27, 2000, Lockheed completed the sale of its Aerospace Electronic Systems business to BAE Systems for $1.67 billion, a deal announced in July 2000.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] This group encompassed Sanders Associates, Fairchild Systems, and Lockheed Martin Space Electronics & Communications.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2001, Lockheed Martin won the contract to build the F-35 Lightning II; this was the largest fighter aircraft procurement project since the F-16, with an initial order of 3,000 aircraft.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2001, Lockheed Martin settled a nine–year investigation conducted by NASA's Office of Inspector General with the assistance of the Defense Contract Audit Agency.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company paid the United States government $7.1 million based on allegations that its predecessor, Lockheed Engineering Science Corporation, submitted false lease costs claims to NASA.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On July 8, 2003, a Lockheed Martin plant in Meridian, Mississippi became the scene of a racially motivated mass shooting when an assembly line worker murdered six co-workers (five of whom were black) and wounded eight before killing himself.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In the immediate aftermath of the shooting, Lockheed Martin's President refused to disclose whether company officials were previously aware of any red flags regarding the worker.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company had launched its own investigation into the worker's behavior prior to the massacre following complaints from numerous black employees regarding incidents involving the worker.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] He had been ordered to attend anger management courses and diversity training but refused.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On May 12, 2006, *The Washington Post* reported that when Robert Stevens took control of Lockheed Martin in 2004, he faced the dilemma that within 10 years, 100,000 of the about 130,000 Lockheed Martin employees – more than three-quarters – would be retiring.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On August 31, 2006, Lockheed Martin won a $3.9 billion contract from NASA to design and build the CEV capsule, later named *Orion* for the Ares I rocket in the Constellation Program.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2009, NASA reduced the capsule crew requirements from the initial six seats to four for transport to the International Space Station.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In August 2007, Lockheed Martin acquired 3Dsolve, a Cary, North Carolina, company that created simulations and training modules for the military and corporate clients.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Renamed Lockheed Martin 3D Learning Systems, the company remained in Cary with 3D's founder Richard Boyd as director.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The name was eventually shortened to Lockheed Martin 3D Solutions.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On August 13, 2008, Lockheed Martin acquired the government business unit of Nantero, Inc., a company that had developed methods and processes for incorporating carbon nanotubes in next-generation electronic devices.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2009, Lockheed Martin bought Unitech.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On November 18, 2010, Lockheed Martin announced that it would be closing its Eagan, Minnesota, location by 2013 to reduce costs and optimize capacity at its locations nationwide.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In January 2011, Lockheed Martin agreed to pay the U.S.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Government $2 million to settle allegations that the company submitted false claims on a U.S. government contract for that amount.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The allegations came from a contract with the Naval Oceanographic Office Major Shared Resource Center in Mississippi.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On May 25, 2011, Lockheed Martin bought the first Quantum Computing System from D-Wave Systems.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin and D-Wave will collaborate to realize the benefits of a computing platform based upon a quantum annealing processor, as applied to some of Lockheed Martin's most challenging computation problems.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin established a multi-year contract that includes one system, maintenance, and services.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On May 28, 2011, it was reported that a cyberattack using previously stolen EMC files had broken through to sensitive materials at the contractor.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] It is unclear if the Lockheed incident is the specific prompt whereby on June 1, 2011, the new United States military strategy, makes explicit that a cyberattack is *casus belli* for a traditional act of war.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Department of Justice (DOJ) said that Lockheed Martin had agreed to settle allegations that the defense contractor had sold overpriced perishable tools used on many contracts.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The DOJ said the allegations were based specifically on the subsidiary Tools & Metals Inc's inflation of costs between 1998 and 2005, which Lockheed Martin then passed on to the U.S. government under its contracts.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Loftis, a former TMI president, was sentenced to 87 months in prison and ordered to pay a fine of $20 million following his guilty plea.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On July 10, 2012, Lockheed Martin announced it was cutting its workforce by 740 workers to reduce costs and remain competitive as necessary for future growth.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On November 27, 2012, Lockheed Martin announced that Marillyn Hewson would become the corporation's chief executive officer on January 1, 2013.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On January 7, 2013, Lockheed Martin Canada announced that it would be acquiring the engine maintenance, repair, and overhaul assets from Aveos Fleet Performance in Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On July 3, 2013, Lockheed Martin announced that it was partnering with DreamHammer to use the company's software for integrated command and control of its unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin teamed up with Bell Helicopter to propose the V-280 Valor tiltrotor for the Future Vertical Lift (FVL) program.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In September 2013, Lockheed Martin acquired the Scotland-based tech firm, Amor Group, saying the deal would aid its plans to expand internationally and into non-defense markets.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On November 14, 2013, Lockheed announced they would be closing their Akron, Ohio facility laying off 500 employees and transferring other employees to other locations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In October 2013, Lockheed announced it expected to finalize a $2.2 billion contract with the United States Air Force for two advanced military communications satellites.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In March 2014, Lockheed Martin acquired Beontra AG, a provider of integrated planning and demand forecasting tools for airport, planning to expand their business in commercial airport information technology solutions.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Also, in March 2014, Lockheed Martin announced its acquisition of Industrial Defender Inc.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On June 2, 2014, Lockheed Martin received a Pentagon contract to build a space fence that would track debris, keeping it from damaging satellites and spacecraft.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On December 20, 2014, Lockheed Martin Integrated Systems agreed to settle a False Claims Act lawsuit paying $27.5 million to finalize allegations that it had knowingly overbilled taxpayers for work performed by company staff who did not hold the relevant essential qualifications for the contract.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On July 20, 2015, Lockheed Martin announced plans to purchase Sikorsky Aircraft from United Technologies Corporation at a cost of $7.1 billion.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The Pentagon has criticized the acquisition as causing a reduction in competition.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In November 2015, the acquisition received final approval from the Chinese government, with a total cost of $9 billion.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Dan Schulz was named the president of Lockheed Martin's Sikorsky company.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin has shown sketches for a twin-engine, blended wing body strategic airlifter similar in size to the C-5.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On March 31, 2015, the US Navy awarded Lockheed Martin a contract worth $362 million for the construction of Freedom-class ship LCS 21 and $79 million for advance procurement for LCS 23.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The Freedom-class ships are built by Fincantieri Marinette Marine in Marinette, Wisconsin.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In December 2015, Lockheed won an $867 million seven-year contract to train Australia's next generation of military pilots.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The deal also has the option to extend this contract across 26 years, which would greatly increase the deal's value.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In August 2016, Canadian Forces Maritime tested an integrated submarine combat system developed by Lockheed Martin.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The test marked Canada's first use of the combat system with the MK 48 heavyweight torpedo, variant 7AT.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The same month, a deal to merge Leidos with the entirety of Lockheed Martin's Information Systems & Global Solutions (IS&GS) business came to a close.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In May 2017, during a visit to Saudi Arabia by President Donald Trump, Saudi Arabia signed business deals worth tens of billions of dollars with U.S. companies, including Lockheed Martin.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On August 13, 2018, Lockheed Martin announced that the company had secured a $480 million contract from the United States Air Force to develop a hypersonic weapon prototype.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] A hypersonic missile can travel at one mile a second.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] This is the second contract for hypersonic weapons that Martin has secured; The first was from the Air Force as well and for $928 million which was announced in April 2018.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On November 29, 2018, Lockheed Martin was awarded a Commercial Lunar Payload Services contract by NASA, which makes it eligible to bid on delivering science and technology payloads to the Moon for NASA, worth $2.6 billion.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] This lander would be based on the successful design of the *Phoenix* and *InSight* Mars landers.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On April 11, 2019, at 6:35 pm EDT, an Arabsat-6A satellite was successfully launched from (LC-39A).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] This satellite is one of two, the other being SaudiGeoSat-1/HellasSat-4 and they are the "most advanced commercial communications satellites ever built by" Lockheed Martin.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On September 23, 2019, Lockheed Martin and NASA signed a $4.6-billion contract to build six or more Orion capsules for NASA's Artemis program to send astronauts to the Moon.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In January 2020, the Naval Sea Systems Command awarded Lockheed Martin with a $138 million contract related with the AEGIS Combat System Engineering Agent (CSEA).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The LMT Rotary and Mission Systems (RMS) unit of the company is to develop, integrate, test, and deliver the AEGIS Advanced Capability Build (ACB) 20 integrated combat system.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Martin will work on the AEGIS in New Jersey.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The project is expected to be completed by December 2020.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In January 2020, the Pentagon found at least 800 software defects in Lockheed Martin's F-35 fighter jets owned by the US Armed Forces during an annual review.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The 2018 and 2019 reviews revealed a large number of defects as well.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In February 2020, Lockheed Martin acquired Vector Launch Inc's satellite software technology GalacticSky for $4.25 million after a bankruptcy court received no bids by the February 21 deadline.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On March 16, 2020, Lockheed Martin announced that James D.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Taiclet would replace Marillyn Hewson as CEO, effective June 15.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In January 2021, Taiclet became chairman of the company as well.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin was sanctioned by the Chinese government in July 2020, October 2020, and February 2023 due to arm sales to Taiwan.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On December 20, 2020, it was announced that Lockheed Martin would acquire Aerojet Rocketdyne Holdings for $4.4 billion.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The acquisition was expected to close in first quarter of 2022.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On February 13, 2022, Lockheed abandoned the deal following regulatory disapproval.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2022, due to the Russo-Ukrainian war, major arms manufacturers, including Lockheed Martin, reported a sharp increase in interim sales and profits.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In May 2023, Lockheed formed a new microelectronics subsidiary ForwardEdge ASIC to design custom application-specific integrated circuits for its customers.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In November 2023, attempts at direct action were taken against arms companies in the US and the UK, including Lockheed Martin, that supplied weapons to Israel during the Gaza war.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2025, Lockheed Martin was included in a UN report on corporations complicit in the Gaza genocide.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In March 2024, Lockheed Martin submitted a bid to acquire Terran Orbital.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Army awarded Lockheed Martin a $4.5 billion contract to supply Patriot Advanced Capability-3 (PAC-3) missiles.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The contract included 870 PAC-3 MSE missiles and related hardware.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed was tasked with manufacturing the newest version of these interceptors, with each PAC-3 MSE missile costing approximately $4 million, as per Army budget documents.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] On October 9, 2024, Lockheed Martin announced the appointment of Chauncey McIntosh as vice president and general manager of the F-35 Lightning II Program, effective December 1, 2024.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] He succeeded Bridget Lauderdale, who retired after 38 years with the company.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In December 2024, Lockheed Martin announced that it had formed a subsidiary, Astris AI, that would help U.S. defense companies to incorporate artificial intelligence into their operations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In May 2026, the company expanded its missile production capacity further with the construction of a new 87,000-square-foot munitions facility in Alabama intended for the production of Terminal High Altitude Area Defense (THAAD) interceptors.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The facility is part of a broader investment plan of approximately $8–9 billion through 2030 aimed at increasing overall missile output.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] For the fiscal year 2020, Lockheed Martin reported earnings of $6.833 billion, with an annual revenue of $65.398 billion, an increase of 9.3% over the previous year.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Backlog was 144.0 billion at the end of 2019, up from 130.5 billion at the end of the 2018.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Firm orders were $94.5 billion at the end of 2019.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Its shares traded at over $389 per share.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Its market capitalization was valued at US$109.83 billion at the end of 2019.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] 60 in the 2019 Fortune 500 list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue (down from No.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed profits sharply dropped 80% in Q2 2025, owing to a highly classified U.S. government aerospace program CEO James Taiclet described as "magical".
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The loss from development of the described "game changing" classified aerospace program totaled $1.6 billion.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Taiclet stated investors would be unable to know details of the "magical" classified aerospace program for many years to come.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] During the same earnings call, Lockheed acknowledged the existence of a classified MFC program, described as game-changing.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The board of directors consists of 14 members.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] As of December 2023, Lockheed Martin shares are mainly held by institutional investors (State Street Corporation, Vanguard group, BlackRock, Capital Group Companies, and others).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin is listed as the largest U.S. government contractor and ranks first for the number of incidents, and fifth for the size of settlements on the 'contractor misconduct' database maintained by the Project on Government Oversight, a Washington, D.C.–based watchdog group.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Since 1995, the company has agreed to pay $676.8 million to settle 88 instances of misconduct.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2015, Lockheed Martin agreed to pay $4.7 million to settle charges that it illegally used taxpayer money to lobby the federal government to block competitors, including by funneling funds through its subsidiary, Sandia Corporation.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] This involved hiring former Representative Heather Wilson, one of the most influential ex-lawmakers in the defense sector, as an unregistered lobbyist to maintain Lockheed's lucrative nuclear weapons lab contracts.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] More broadly, commentators have criticized Lockheed Martin and other weapons defense firms for using secretive spending and dark money to influence defense policy, raising concerns about reduced accountability and national security risks.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Christopher Bogdan criticized the company's F-35 fighter program.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The general said: "I want them both to start behaving like they want to be around for 40 years ...
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] I want them to take on some of the risk of this program.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] I want them to invest in cost reductions.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] I want them to do the things that will build a better relationship.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] I'm not getting all that love yet." The criticism came in the wake of previous criticism from former Defense Secretary Robert Gates regarding the same program.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin has highlighted the conflicts in Gaza and Ukraine as potential opportunities for future revenue growth.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In March 2026, a panel of the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals revived a qui tam lawsuit in *United States ex rel.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin Corp.* The case involves allegations that the company violated the Truth in Negotiations Act and the False Claims Act by providing inaccurate labor cost data during negotiations for the F-35 program.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] According to the magazine *Politico*, Lockheed Martin has "a political network that is already the envy of its competitors", and its contracts enjoy wide bipartisan support in the U.S.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Congress thanks to it having "perfected the strategy of spreading jobs on weapons programs in key states and congressional districts".
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The company's 2022 lobbying expenditure is $13.6 million (2009 total: $13.7 million).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Through its political action committee (PAC), the company provides low levels of financial support to candidates who advocate national defense and relevant business issues.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] It was the largest contributor to the House Armed Services Committee chairman, Republican Buck McKeon of California with over $50,000 donated in the election cycle as of January 2011.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Daniel Inouye (D-HI), the chair of the Senate Appropriations Committee before his death in 2012.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin Employees Political Action Committee is one of the 50 largest in the country, according to FEC data.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] With contributions from 3,000 employees, it donates $500,000 a year to about 260 House and Senate candidates.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] In 2025, Lockheed Martin was one of the donors who funded the Trump administration's East Wing demolition, and planned building of a ballroom.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] A 2026 report found that no single donor to Trump's ballroom project subsequently received more federal government contracts than Lockheed Martin.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Senior management consists of the CEO, CFO, and Executive Vice Presidents (EVPs) of four business areas.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The EVPs are responsible for managing major programs.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed also announced that it would create the chief operating officer role, to which current EVP Frank A.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Floor or touch workers belong to component assembly teams.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin manages and maintains its relationship with these touch workers through its supervisors and unions.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Lockheed Martin manages employees through its Full Spectrum Leadership and LM21 programs.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The LM21 program relies on Six Sigma principles, which are techniques to improve efficiency.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Senior management constructs leadership councils and assigns managers to facilitate Kaizen events, which target specific processes for improvement.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] A manager facilitates teams and processes stakeholders and suppliers to streamline process implementation.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Tier 2 Functional Leads and Tier 3 IPT Leads report to Tier 1.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] IPT leads are responsible for entire systems or products defined by the contract's Statement of Work.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] To control quality, Lockheed Martin trains and builds IPT teams. and ensures that work is executed correctly through a Technical Performance Measure (TPM) system which emphasizes its Lean and 6 Sigma processes.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Middle management uses commitment mechanisms that parallel high commitment and human relations theory.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] Floor employees assemble aircraft using Flow-to-takt lean manufacturing process which uses properties from both division of labor and scientific management.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] By separating tasks based on parts, Lockheed Martin utilizes the division of labor theory, specialization on a specific area creates efficiency.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] The "Double Helix methodology" is a systems development methodology used by Lockheed Martin.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/lockheed-martin] It combines experimentation, technology, and a warfighter's concept of operations to create new tactics and weapons.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] In military operations, **reconnaissance** (/rɪˈkɒnɪsəns/) or **scouting** is the exploration of an area by military forces to obtain information about enemy forces, the terrain, and civil activities in the area of operations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] In military jargon, reconnaissance is abbreviated to *recce* (in British, Canadian, Australian English) and to *recon* (in American English), both derived from the root word *reconnoitre* / *reconnoitering*.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The types of reconnaissance include patrolling the local area of operations and long-range reconnaissance patrols, which are tasks usually realized in the United States of America by U.S.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Army Rangers, cavalry scouts, and military intelligence specialists, using navy ships and submarines, reconnaissance aircraft, satellites to collect raw intelligence; and establishing observation posts.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Moreover, espionage is different from reconnaissance, because spies work as civilians in enemy territory.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] — Reconnaissance (US Army FM 7-92; Chap.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The word is derived from the Middle French *reconoissance*, meaning "recognition".
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Reconnaissance conducted by ground forces includes special reconnaissance, armored reconnaissance, amphibious reconnaissance and civil reconnaissance.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Aerial reconnaissance is reconnaissance carried out by aircraft (of all types including balloons and uncrewed aircraft).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The purpose is to survey weather conditions, map terrain, and may include military purposes such as observing tangible structures, particular areas, and movement of enemy forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Naval forces use aerial and satellite reconnaissance to observe enemy forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Navies also undertake hydrographic surveys and intelligence gathering.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Reconnaissance satellites provide military commanders with photographs of enemy forces and other intelligence.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Military forces also use geographical and meteorological information from Earth observation satellites.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The techniques and objectives are not mutually exclusive; it is up to the commander whether they are carried out separately or by the same unit.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Reconnaissance-in-force (RIF) is a type of military operation or military tactic used specifically to probe an enemy's combat ability.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] While typical reconnaissance forces are small and armed only for self-defense, RIF use considerable (but not decisive) force in order to elicit a strong reaction by the enemy that more accurately reveals its own strength, deployment, preparedness, determination, and other tactical data.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The RIF units can then fall back and report this data, or expand the conflict into a full engagement if enemy weaknesses are revealed.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Other methods consist of hit-and-run tactics using rapid mobility, and in some cases light-armored vehicles for added fire superiority, as the need arises.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Maintaining active RIF can be used to limit, or even deny, enemy reconnaissance.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Reconnaissance-by-fire (or *speculative fire*) is the act of firing at likely enemy positions to cause the enemy force to reveal their location by moving or by returning fire.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Reconnaissance-pull is a tactic that is applied at the regiment to division level and defined as locating and rapidly exploiting enemy weaknesses.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] It is the ability to determine enemy positions and create exploitable gaps through which friendly forces can pass while avoiding obstacles and strong points.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] A textbook example of reconnaissance-pull was documented during the Tinian landings of World War II, utilized by the United States Marine Corps's Amphibious Reconnaissance Battalion, from V Amphibious Corps.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Aerial photography and the confirmation by the amphibious reconnaissance platoons determined that the Japanese defenders had largely ignored the northern beaches of the island, focusing most of their defensive effort on beaches in the south-west which were more favorable for an amphibious landing.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] American forces quickly changed their landing location to the northern beaches and planned a small and hasty "deception" operation off the southern beach, which resulted in a complete surprise for the Japanese forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] As a result, American forces were able to fight the Japanese force on land, where they had the advantage, leading to light losses and a relatively short battle that lasted only 9 days.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] When referring to reconnaissance, a commander's full intention is to have a vivid picture of his battlespace.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] This analysis determines whether the platoon uses single or multiple elements to conduct the reconnaissance, whether it pertains to **area**, **zone**, or **route reconnaissance**, the following techniques may be used as long as the fundamentals of reconnaissance are applied.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Sanitary epidemiological reconnaissance implies collection and transfer of all data available on sanitary and epidemiological situation of the area of possible deployment and action of armed forces, the same data for the neighboring and enemy armed forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The aim for the reconnaissance is to clear up the reasons of the specific disease origin- sources of the infection in various extreme situations, including local wars and armed conflicts, the ways of the infection transfer and all factors promoting to the infestation.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] After the armed forces have become stationary during wartime and emergency of peacetime the sanitary epidemiological reconnaissance turns into sanitary and epidemiological surveillance and medical control of vital and communal activity of the armed forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Area reconnaissance refers to the observation, and information obtained, about a specified location and the area around it; it may be terrain-oriented and/or force-oriented.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Ideally, a reconnaissance platoon, or team, would use surveillance or vantage (static) points around the objective to observe, and the surrounding area.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] This methodology focuses mainly prior to moving forces into or near a specified area; the military commander may utilize his reconnaissance assets to conduct an area reconnaissance to avoid being surprised by unsuitable terrain conditions, or most importantly, unexpected enemy forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The area could be a town, ridge-line, woods, or another feature that friendly forces intend to occupy, pass through, or avoid.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Within an area of operation (AO), area reconnaissance can focus the reconnaissance on the specific area that is critical to the commander.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] This technique of focusing the reconnaissance also permits the mission to be accomplished more quickly.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Area reconnaissance can thus be a stand-alone mission or a task to a section or the platoon.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The commander analyzes the mission to determine whether the platoon will conduct these types of reconnaissance separately or in conjunction with each other.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Civil reconnaissance is the process of gathering a broad spectrum of civil information about a specific population in support of military operations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] It is related to and often performed in conjunction with infrastructure reconnaissance (assessment and survey).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Normally the focus of collection in the operational area for civil reconnaissance is collecting civil information relating to the daily interaction between civilians and military forces.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Civil information encompasses relational, temporal, geospatial and behavioral information captured in a socio-cultural backdrop.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] It is information developed from data related to civil areas, structures, capabilities, organizations, people, and events, within the civil component of the commander's operational environment that can be processed to increase situational awareness and understanding.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The type of civil information that is needed in order to support military operations varies based on the environment and situation.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Route reconnaissance is oriented on a given route (e.g., a road, a railway, a waterway; i.e., a narrow axis or a general direction of attack) to provide information on route conditions or activities along the route.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] A military commander relies on information about locations along his determined route: which of those that would provide best cover and concealment; bridge by construction type, dimensions, and classification; or for landing zones or pickup zones, if the need arises.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] In many cases, the commander may act upon a *force-oriented* route reconnaissance by which the enemy could influence movement along that route.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] For the reconnaissance platoons, or squads, stealth and speed—in conjunction with detailed intelligence-reporting—are most important and crucial.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The reconnaissance platoon must remain far enough ahead of the maneuver force to assist in early warning and to prevent the force from becoming surprised.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] It is paramount to obtain information about the available space in which a force can maneuver without being forced to bunch up due to obstacles.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] This requirement includes the size of trees and the density of forests due to their effects on vehicle movement.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Route reconnaissance also allows the observation for fields of fire along the route and adjacent terrain.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] This information assists planners as a supplement to map information.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Zone reconnaissance focuses on obtaining detailed information before maneuvering their forces through particular, designated locations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] It can be terrain-oriented, force-oriented, or both, as it acquire this information by reconnoitering within—and by maintaining surveillance over—routes, obstacles (to include nuclear-radiological, biological, and chemical contamination), and resources within an assigned location.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Also, *force-oriented* zone reconnaissance is assigned to gain detailed information about enemy forces within the zone, or when the enemy situation is vague by which the information concerning cross-country traffic-ability is desired.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] The reconnaissance provides the commander with a detailed picture of how the enemy has occupied the zone, enabling him to choose the appropriate course-of-action.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] As the platoon conducts this type of zone reconnaissance, its emphasis is on determining the enemy's locations, strengths, and weaknesses.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] This is the most thorough and complete reconnaissance mission and therefore is very time-intensive.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] A tracker needs to pay close attention to both the environment and the psychology of their enemy.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/reconnaissance] Knowledge of human psychology, sociology, and cultural backgrounds is necessary to know the actions of the enemy and what they will do or where they will go next.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/tactics-enterprise] Tactics represent the "why" of an ATT&CK technique or sub-technique.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/tactics-enterprise] It is the adversary's tactical goal: the reason for performing an action.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/tactics-enterprise] For example, an adversary may want to achieve credential access.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] In computer security, a **threat** is a potential negative action or event enabled by a vulnerability that results in an unwanted impact to a computer system or application.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] A threat can be either a negative "intentional" event like hacking or an "accidental" negative event or otherwise a circumstance, capability, action, or event (incident is often used as a blanket term).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] A *threat actor* who is an individual or group that can perform the threat action, such as exploiting a vulnerability to actualise a negative impact.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] An *exploit* is a vulnerability that a threat actor used to cause an incident.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and others involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The attack can be *active* when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises Integrity or Availability.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] A "*passive attack*" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources: so it compromises Confidentiality.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] OWASP (see figure) depicts the same phenomenon in slightly different terms: a threat agent through an attack vector exploits a weakness (vulnerability) of the system and the related security controls causing a technical impact on an IT resource (asset) connected to a business impact.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Countermeasures are also called security controls; when applied to the transmission of information are named security services.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The overall picture represents the risk factors of the risk scenario.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The widespread of computer dependencies and the consequent raising of the consequence of a successful attack, led to a new term cyberwarfare.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Nowadays the many real attacks exploit Psychology at least as much as technology.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Phishing and Pretexting and other methods are called social engineering techniques.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The Web 2.0 applications, specifically Social network services, can be a mean to get in touch with people in charge of system administration or even system security, inducing them to reveal sensitive information.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Note that a threat type can have multiple origins.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Recent trends in computer threats show an increase in ransomware attacks, supply chain attacks, and fileless malware.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Ransomware attacks involve the encryption of a victim's files and a demand for payment to restore access.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Supply chain attacks target the weakest links in a supply chain to gain access to high-value targets.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Fileless malware attacks use techniques that allow malware to run in memory, making it difficult to detect.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Microsoft previously rated the risk of security threats using five categories in a classification called DREAD: Risk assessment model.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The spread over a network of threats can lead to dangerous situations.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] In military and civil fields, threat level has been defined: for example INFOCON is a threat level used by the US.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Leading antivirus software vendors publish global threat level on their websites.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a threat actor (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Threat actors are commonly analysed according to their motivations, resources, technical capability, access to systems, relationship to a target, and degree of connection to state authority.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] They may exploit vulnerabilities, conduct social engineering, steal or monetise data, disrupt operations, or support other actors who carry out such activity.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Because the term covers a wide range of actors, researchers and security organisations use taxonomies that distinguish between groups such as cybercriminals, state-linked actors, ideologically motivated actors, thrill seekers or trolls, insiders, and competitors.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Threat actor classifications are used in risk management, cyber threat intelligence, and incident response to connect observed behaviour with possible objectives and likely future activity.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The categories are not always mutually exclusive: the same actor may combine criminal, ideological, commercial, or state-linked motivations, and different organisations may use different names for similar actors.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] A collection of threats in a particular domain or context, with information on identified vulnerable assets, threats, risks, threat actors and observed trends.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Threats should be managed by operating an ISMS, performing all the IT risk management activities foreseen by laws, standards and methodologies.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Very large organizations tend to adopt business continuity management plans in order to protect, maintain and recover business-critical processes and systems.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Some of these plans are implemented by computer security incident response team (CSIRT).
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Threat management must identify, evaluate, and categorize threats.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Many organizations perform only a subset of these methods, adopting countermeasures based on a non-systematic approach, resulting in *computer insecurity*.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Information security awareness is a significant market.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] There has been a lot of software developed to deal with IT threats, including both open-source software and proprietary software.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Threat management involves a wide variety of threats including physical threats like flood and fire.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] While ISMS risk assessment process does incorporate threat management for cyber threats such as remote buffer overflows the risk assessment process doesn't include processes such as threat intelligence management or response procedures.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] Cyber threat management (CTM) is emerging as the best practice for managing cyber threats beyond the basic risk assessment found in ISMS.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] It enables early identification of threats, data-driven situational awareness, accurate decision-making, and timely threat mitigating actions.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] The SANS Institute has conducted research and surveys on the effectiveness of threat hunting to track and disrupt cyber adversaries as early in their process as possible.
[src:cyber-kill-chain/threat-computer-security] According to a survey performed in 2019, "61% [of the respondents] report at least an 11% measurable improvement in their overall security posture" and 23.6% of the respondents have experienced a 'significant improvement' in reducing the dwell time.
